==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gloss
<hw>Gloss</hw> <pr>(gl⟦ocr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Icel.
<ets>glossi</ets> a blaze, <ets>glys</ets> finery, MHG.
<ets>glosen</ets> to glow, G. <ets>glosten</ets> to glimmer; perh. akin
to E. <ets>glass</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Brightness or luster of
a body proceeding from a smooth surface; polish; <as>as, the
<ex>gloss</ex> of silk; cloth is calendered to give it a
<ex>gloss</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is no part . . . to set on the face of this cause any fairer
<qex>gloss</qex> than the naked truth doth afford.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A specious appearance; superficial quality or
show.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To me more dear, congenial to my heart,⟦br⟧
One native charm than all the <qex>gloss</qex> of art.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gloss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gloss
<hw>Gloss</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Glossed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Glossing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To give a superficial luster or
gloss to; to make smooth and shining; <as>as, to <ex>gloss</ex>
cloth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>glossed</qex> and gleamy wave.</q> <rj><qau>J. R.
Drake.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gloss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Gloss
<hw>Gloss</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>glose</ets>, F.
<ets>glose</ets>, L. <ets>glossa</ets> a difficult word needing
explanation, fr. Gr. <?/ tongue, language, word needing explanation. Cf.
<er>Gloze</er>, <er>Glossary</er>, <er>Glottis</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A foreign, archaic, technical, or other uncommon
word requiring explanation.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An interpretation, consisting of one or more words,
interlinear or marginal; an explanatory note or comment; a running
commentary.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All this, without a <qex>gloss</qex> or comment,⟦br⟧
He would unriddle in a moment.</q> <rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Explaining the text in short <qex>glosses</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>T.
Baker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A false or specious explanation.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 632 --></p>

<p><ent>Gloss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Gloss
<hw>Gloss</hw> <pr>(gl⟦ocr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
render clear and evident by comments; to illustrate; to explain; to
annotate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give a specious appearance to; to render specious
and plausible; to palliate by specious explanation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You have the art to <qex>gloss</qex> the foulest cause.</q>
<rj><qau>Philips.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gloss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Gloss
<hw>Gloss</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make
comments; to comment; to explain.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make sly remarks, or insinuations.</def>
<rj><au>Prior.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glossa</ent>⟦br⟧
